description: Acianthus ledwardii was a terrestrial, perennial, deciduous, sympodial herb with a single heart-shaped, glabrous, pale green leaf that was reddish-purple on its lower surface. Each plant had between 2 and 6 deep purplish or reddish brown flowers on a thin raceme up to 50 mm (2.0 in) tall. The flowers were similar to those of the more common Acianthus fornicatus, but the dorsal sepal narrowed abruptly rather than gradually tapered, the lateral sepals had three points on the tip, the petals were broader than those of A. fornicatus, and the labellum was convex on the lower surface, rather than concave. - wiki

The Black-tipped Spider-orchid flowers from late September to early November and in flower, the plants are 10–20 cm tall with a wiry and densely hairy stalk bearing a single flower. The flower is 45–65 mm across and is white to cream with pale reddish lines and prominent black tail-like extensions. The dorsal sepal is 35–55 mm long and 2–3 mm wide. The lateral sepals are 35–55 mm long and 3.5–5 mm wide and the petals are 35–45 mm long and 2–3 mm wide. The labellum is white to cream with dark reddish purple calli and the column behind the labellum is translucent with reddish markings. The leaf of the Black-tipped Spider-orchid is densely haired with a purple blotched base and is 5–12 cm long and 3–7 mm wide (Threatened Species Unit 2001b).

Small shrub; branches sprawling, prostrate or decumbent, c. 35 cm long, striate or ridged, with scattered, peltate, fusiform hairs. Leaves alternate, obovate, obtuse, emarginate or rarely acute at the apex, mucronate, tapered into the petiole, 4-16 x 2.5-5 mm, ± complicate, with appressed hairs or almost glabrous; margins slightly recurved; venation brochidodromous, midrib raised on the underside; petioles 0.5-1.5 mm long; stipules subulate, c. 1 mm long, persistent. Racemes terminal, 7-18 cm long with up to 30 flowers. Pedicels 2-2.5 mm long; bracts narrow-ovate, 1.5-2mm long, persistent; bracteoles very narrow-ovate, c. 0.75 mm long, attached to the pedicel close to the calyx, persistent. Calyx tapered at the base, 3.5-4.5 mm long, with peltate, fusiform hairs; upper two lobes united into a truncate emarginate lip, the tips free c. 0.75 mm; lower three lobes a little shorter, acute, c. 1.75 mm long. Corella dull yellow with red-brown markings: standard depressed ovate, shallowly emarginate, 7-9 x 7-9 mm including 3.5-4 mm long claw; wings oblong-obovate, curved, scarcely auriculate, 7-8 x 2-2.5 mm including 2-2.5 mm claw; keel almost as long as the wings, ± ovate, acuminate or attenuate at the apex, rarely acute, partly inflated, auriculate, 6-7.5 x 1.5-2.5 mm including 2-3 mm claw. Stamens with filaments 4-.6 mm long; anthers versatile, c. 0.4 mm long. Gynoecium 6-7 mm long including 11.5 mm stipe and gently incurved style 1.75-2.5 mm; stigma capitate, very small; ovary with dense, appressed hairs; ovules 14-21. Pod and seed not seen.
habitat: red loam, brown sandy clay with decomposing granite or in clay soils, on plains in scrub or open tree mallee.

description: The austral pipewort is a small, semi-aquatic, annual herb with a basal tuft of linear leaves 2050 mm long and 1–1.5 mm wide. Flowers are egg-shaped to almost globular with heads 3–4 mm wide. These flower heads are enclosed by lance-shaped outer bracts and linear inner bracts. The fruits are smooth, with 3 celled capsules, each containing a single seed (description from Cunningham et al. 1992).

description: Tree, occasionally multi-trunked, up to 15 m tall. Bark light grey, flaky, box-type, persistent on trunk and branches >50 mm in diameter, smooth above, shedding in short ribbons. Seedling leaves disjunct, ovate, dull green, moderately discolorous, margins entire, apex acute. Juvenile leaves disjunct, ovate to broad-ovate, dull green, concolorous, apex acute to acuminate. Adult leaves disjunct, broad lanceolate, 10–15 cm long, 2.6– 4.1 cm wide, green, semiglossy, concolorous, apex acuminate; intramarginal veins moderately distant from margin, secondary venation acutely angled; tertiary venation visible; oil glands scattered, intersectional. Conflorescence compound, terminal, sometimes axillary unbranched; umbellasters 7-flowered, up to 6 per conflorescence; peduncle angular to terete, 6–8.5 mm long; pedicels terete, 0.5–1 mm long. Floral buds clavate to shortly fusiform, 9–12 mm long, 4–4.5 mm in diameter, non-glaucous, green; scar present; calyptra hemispherical to conical, 1.3–1.8 mm long, 2.8–3.2 mm wide, shorter and narrower than hypanthium. Outer stamens infertile; anthers cuboid. Fruit conical, 7–9.8 mm long, 6.2–7.8 mm in diameter, nonglaucous; disc descending or level; valves 3 or 4, enclosed. Fertile seeds dark brown, ovoid to D-shaped, finely reticulate; hilum ventral.

description: Compact, erect to spreading, rounded shrubs to 1.2 m high; branchlets densely silvery-sericeous with appressed hairs, eventually becoming glabrous with the development of reddish-brown, smooth bark decorticating in strips and flakes. Leaves erect to spreading, alternate, elliptic to slightly obovate, 12–25 mm long, 4–7 mm wide, flat, both surfaces densely and closely silvery appressed-sericeous with hairs ~1.5 mm long; apex acute. Flowers sessile, terminal and axillary on short shoots in the upper leaf axils, closely subtended by floral leaves; bracts 3 or 4, brown, scarious, broadly ovate, acute, 3–4 mm long, shortly sericeous. Sepals narrowly triangular, 6–9 mm long, densely appressed silvery silky-sericeous with hairs ~1.5 mm long; midribs not prominent; outer sepals acute; inner sepals in size, apex shape and indumentum similar to the outer sepals, but broader and with broad, scarious margins. Petals yellow, obovate, 6–9 mm long, emarginate. Stamens 21–27, more or less evenly distributed around the carpels, spreading-erect, free; filaments 1.5–2.5 mm long; anthers rectangular, 1.0–1.4 mm long, dehiscing by short, terminal slits. Staminodes absent or few. Carpels 2; ovaries ±globular, glabrous; styles ±erect to spreading, excentrically placed on the carpel apex, 2–4 mm long. Ovules 2 per carpel. Seeds not seen.

description: A delicate shrub with branches to approximately 50 cm long. Its branches, linear leaves and floral parts are covered with small, fine star-shaped hairs. The species flowers all year around and has five-petalled, bright yellow flowers on slender stalks, which droop after flowering (Toelken, 1995).

Isoglossa is a herb that grows to 50 cm tall. Its paired leaves are oval or more elongated and 2 – 16 cm long. The white-petalled flowers are about 12 mm across, and are borne in clusters towards the tops of the stems. The five petals are of three kinds: two are erect, two droop to the sides and a central tube-like structure has three lobes. The capsules are up to 12 mm long, and tapered at each end to form an elongated diamond shape. They spring open, expelling seeds explosively.

description: Prostanthera sp. Dunmore (D.M.Gordon 84), Family Lamiaceae, is a low, upright, shrub to 1 m tall. Leaves are whorled on the stem, linear, 0.8–1.2 cm long, 1–2 mm wide and have no stalks. The leaf margins curve downwards and inwards to the stem. Flower stems are at the ends of branches. The flowers are on stalks to 2 mm long, are mauve to purple-blue and about 8 mm long (Stanley & Ross, 1986; Queensland Herbarium, 2008).

description: Stylidium asymmetricum is an annual herb 2–16 cm high, with subulate leaves that are scattered on the stem or arranged in a basal rosette (sometimes rotting if submerged in water). The inflorescence has 1–26 flowers with glandular-hairy pedicels 3–15 mm long. The hypanthium is obloid, 2–6 mm long and sparsely glandular-hairy or subglabrous; the calyx has 3 distinct and 2 connate lobes. The corolla is pale or bright pink with white at the base (rarely white with pink markings) and the throat is yellow; the corolla lobes are asymmetrically arranged, with the morphologically lower ones paired laterally and the upper ones spreading (the upper posterior lobe is angled at ± 90º to the anterior one). There are 4–8, yellow throat appendages. The column is 4.8–5.5 mm long and operates laterally. Capsules are obloid to cylindrical and c. 6–9 mm long excluding calyx lobes. See Wege (2011) for additional information.

description: Tephrosia leveillei, Family Fabaceae, is a low growing perennial herb to 30 cm tall. The leaves are without stalks, and have 5–9 leaflets (the lower leaves often with three leaflets) and are 1.5–2.5 cm long. The leaflets are opposite, narrowly oblong-elliptic, 1.75–3 cm long and 4–7 mm wide, the terminal leaflets are larger than the others. Flowers are solitary or paired on leaf axils. The calyx is nearly 5 mm long and densely hairy; the three lower calyx lobes are longer than the upper ones. The corolla is present only on juveniles and shorter than the calyx when seen. The pod is linear, hairy, 3–3.5 cm long and 5 mm wide. There are usually 6 seeds approximately 3.5 mm long (Domin, 1926). Tephrosia leveillei is very closely allied to T. flagellaris, and taxonomic work is required to determine the relationship between these species (L. Pedley, 2008, pers. comm.)
